You are maintaining an enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System built as a monorepo.

Refactoring must be controlled, safe, and justified.
Stability is more important than perfection.

==============================
GENERAL PRINCIPLE
==============================

Do NOT perform large structural refactors unless explicitly requested by the developer.

Small, incremental improvements are acceptable when they clearly reduce complexity.
Large architectural changes require explicit approval before implementation.

==============================
WHEN REFACTORING IS ALLOWED
==============================

Refactoring is allowed only when:

- Fixing a bug that requires structural change to resolve properly.
- Reducing clearly duplicated logic (DRY violation across modules).
- Improving readability without changing external behavior.
- Improving performance with measurable justification.
- Extracting shared logic into packages/shared when duplication is found between apps.
- Aligning code with established patterns when a module deviates from project conventions.

==============================
WHAT YOU MUST NOT DO
==============================

- Do not move NestJS modules between folders without explicit request.
- Do not rename files globally without request.
- Do not change the monorepo folder structure (apps/, packages/, docs/).
- Do not replace NestJS patterns with Express patterns.
- Do not replace Prisma with raw SQL or another ORM.
- Do not introduce new libraries without approval.
- Do not rewrite working features completely.
- Do not change the shared package (@crm/shared) API surface without checking all consumers.
- Do not alter database schema outside of a planned feature.
- Do not refactor frontend and backend simultaneously — change one side, verify, then the other.

==============================
SAFE REFACTOR RULES
==============================

If refactoring:

- Keep changes minimal and focused on a single concern.
- Do not change API contracts (request/response shapes).
- Do not change database schema (Prisma migrations) unless part of a feature.
- Maintain backward compatibility with existing endpoints.
- Preserve existing route paths and response formats.
- If renaming a shared type in @crm/shared, update ALL consumers (api + web) in the same change.
- Run existing functionality after refactor to verify nothing is broken.

==============================
MONOREPO-SPECIFIC RULES
==============================

- Changing packages/shared affects both apps/api and apps/web.
  Always verify impact on both apps before modifying shared code.
- Moving a type from a local app to packages/shared is allowed and encouraged (deduplication).
- Moving a type from packages/shared back to a local app is NOT allowed without approval.
- When refactoring backend services, verify that API response shapes remain unchanged.
- When refactoring frontend components, verify that they still conform to the design system.

==============================
ANALYZE BEFORE MODIFYING
==============================

Before any refactoring, explain:

1. WHAT will change — list specific files and modules affected.
2. WHY it is necessary — reference a concrete problem (duplication, bug, performance).
3. RISK assessment — what could break, which endpoints or pages are affected.
4. SCOPE — is it contained to one module or does it cross module boundaries?

If risk is high or scope crosses multiple modules, suggest the change and wait for approval.

==============================
PRIORITY ORDER
==============================

When making decisions, follow this priority:

1. Stability — working code stays working
2. Security — never weaken security for cleaner code
3. Maintainability — code should be easy to understand and modify
4. Performance — optimize only when measurably needed
5. Code elegance — nice-to-have, never at the cost of the above

Never sacrifice stability for elegance.
Never sacrifice security for developer convenience.
